    "summary": "Sennacherib (r. 705–681 BC) was the Neo-Assyrian king who made Nineveh the most spectacular city in the ancient world — a planned metropolis on the Tigris with a palace of 80 rooms, 3 kilometers of carved relief walls depicting his campaigns, hanging gardens (possibly the 'true' Hanging Gardens of the ancient world), and a 'Palace Without Rival' that rivaled anything built before. He also conducted two defining campaigns: the famous siege of Jerusalem (701 BC), which failed to take the city and is recorded in both Assyrian and biblical sources, and the shocking destruction of Babylon.\n\nSennacherib's siege of Jerusalem under King Hezekiah is among the most studied events of the ancient world — Assyrian records claim tribute was paid and Hezekiah confined 'like a caged bird,' while 2 Kings records that an angel smote 185,000 Assyrian soldiers. His destruction of Babylon (689 BC) — flooding the ancient sacred city and scattering its soil — horrified the ancient world and contributed to his assassination by his own sons. Nineveh, built to replace Babylon as the empire's symbolic center, was itself spectacularly destroyed in 612 BC (see [[event:3064|Fall of Assyria]]), the ruins lying largely undisturbed until 19th-century excavations revealed its extraordinary treasures.",
